Hell, no.
To make you my new intern.

120
00:06:01,905 --> 00:06:03,362
You're a real go-getter.

121
00:06:03,376 --> 00:06:04,920
Now go get me
my dry-cleaning,

122
00:06:04,937 --> 00:06:06,623
which is my code word
for scotch.

123
00:06:06,625 --> 00:06:08,020
And get me a scotch,

124
00:06:08,025 --> 00:06:09,913
which is my code word
for my bookie.

125
00:06:09,915 --> 00:06:11,773
Also, go get
my dry-cleaning.

126
00:06:11,777 --> 00:06:14,273
- Wha... but...
- Wha, but, wha, wha, wha, but.

127
00:06:14,277 --> 00:06:15,620
What are you standing
around for?

128
00:06:15,625 --> 00:06:18,273
I wish I was paying you,
so I could dock your salary.

129
00:06:20,198 --> 00:06:21,871
Lisa didn't know it then,

130
00:06:21,886 --> 00:06:25,552
but she had just dipped her
toe into the business of show.

131
00:06:25,556 --> 00:06:30,430
And it is a business, as you shall
find out in about three seconds.

132
00:06:30,436 --> 00:06:32,221
Two... one...

133
00:06:32,688 --> 00:06:34,971
Over the years, show business

134
00:06:34,975 --> 00:06:36,980
has been home to scoundrels and saints,

135
00:06:36,986 --> 00:06:40,281
thespians and harlequins,
Abbots and Costelli.

136
00:06:40,286 --> 00:06:42,702
And they all had one thing
in common...

137
00:06:42,715 --> 00:06:45,101
an underpaid assistant.

138
00:06:45,116 --> 00:06:48,713
