Long John Seltzer!

253
00:12:21,966 --> 00:12:24,561
The laughter swept
over her like a wave,

254
00:12:24,568 --> 00:12:27,962
enveloping her in its
intoxicating embrace.

255
00:12:27,997 --> 00:12:31,300
The next week, Krusty went
to his Lake Tahoe retreat

256
00:12:31,298 --> 00:12:33,553
** for some R and R.

257
00:12:33,557 --> 00:12:36,253
But he was about
to get an unexpected visit

258
00:12:36,255 --> 00:12:38,281
from a third and fourth R,

259
00:12:38,286 --> 00:12:40,580
Ron Rabinowitz.

260
00:12:40,775 --> 00:12:43,260
Krusty, I've been your
agent for 45 years.

261
00:12:43,265 --> 00:12:46,400
I am telling you, watch out
for this Lisa Simpson character.

262
00:12:46,408 --> 00:12:48,320
She has got a taste
for Lady Laughter,

263
00:12:48,325 --> 00:12:50,753
and she will step right over
a certain clown to get it.

264
00:12:50,758 --> 00:12:52,410
Which clown?
Chuckles?

265
00:12:52,418 --> 00:12:53,691
Professor Nitwit?

266
00:12:53,705 --> 00:12:54,791
No, you!

267
00:12:54,797 --> 00:12:57,843
No Yu,
the Chinese Clown?

268
00:12:59,486 --> 00:13:02,110
Oh, great one, Krusty.

269
00:13:02,115 --> 00:13:04,510
But seriously,
you're in real trouble here.

270
00:13:05,018 --> 00:13:06,173
Yeah?

271
00:13:06,177 --> 00:13:07,302
What do you mean?

272
00:13:07,608 --> 00:13:10,400
If there was a rehearsal
for the network,

273
00:13:10,405 --> 00:13:12,743
I would've been told by my...

274
00:13:13,316 --> 00:13:15,451
...assistant!

275
00:13:15,456 --> 00:13:16,840
Well, where is he?

276
00:13:16,845 --> 00:13:18,852
I don't know,
I guess he forgot.

277
00:13:18,858 --> 00:13:21,352
But people seemed
to like me last week.

278
00:13:21,366 --> 00:13:23,022
You stood in
for Mr. Teeny.

279
00:13:23,035 --> 00:13:24,691
How'd you like to stand in
for Krusty?

280
00:13:24,695 --> 00:13:28,320
Oh, well, it's one thing
to fill in for a monkey.

281
00:13:28,335 --> 00:13:30,000
But a comedy legend?

282
00:13:30,006 --> 00:13:31,422
I wouldn't dream of it.

283
00:13:31,505 --> 00:13:33,412
I respect that.
Cancel the run-through.

284
00:13:33,415 --> 00:13:34,932
Okay, I'll do the monologue.

285
00:13:36,507 --> 00:13:38,002
Evening, Mr. Krusty.

286
00:13:38,008 --> 00:13:40,843
- Great show last...
- Sorry, I can't act like you matter!

287
00:13:46,828 --> 00:13:49,142
Have no fear,
the star is here!

288
00:13:49,148 --> 00:13:50,620
Shh!
We're working!

289
00:13:50,655 --> 00:13:51,842
Huh?

290
00:13:51,896 --> 00:13:54,612
So the centipede says:
"I'm goin'! I'm goin'!

291
00:13:54,615 --> 00:13:56,920
I'm just putting on my shoes!"

292
00:13:58,605 --> 00:14:01,583
Now, that's well-performed comedy!

293
00:14:01,586 --> 00:14:03,420
Oh, my God.

294
00:14:03,428 --> 00:14:05,962
Everything you said
came true, Ron.

295
00:14:05,968 --> 00:14:06,920
Uh, Ron?

296
00:14:06,938 --> 00:14:10,613
So you'll come to the agency tomorrow and
I'll introduce you to the whole team, okay?

297
00:14:10,615 --> 00:14:11,991
You like egg white omelets?

298
00:14:11,997 --> 00:14:14,183
I'll be waiting.
You're a good girl.

299
00:14:15,106 --> 00:14:18,032
I've been replaced by
an eight-year-old.

300
00:14:18,036 --> 00:14:19,230
I can be eight!

301
00:14:19,937 --> 00:14:21,593
La, la, la, la.

302
00:14:21,597 --> 00:14:23,611
I'm eight years old.

303
00:14:29,896 --> 00:14:33,863
Krusty, you've learned that fame,
that fickle beauty,

304
00:14:33,865 --> 00:14:35,911
can leave you when
you need it most.

305
00:14:35,916 --> 00:14:38,782
And Lisa had a lesson
to learn as well.

306
00:14:38,786 --> 00:14:40,782
A lesson about...
You, there!

307
00:14:40,787 --> 00:14:42,893
- Cut that out!
- Sorry, sorry.

308
00:14:45,777 --> 00:14:48,993
Thank you, folks.
You've been a great audience.

309
00:14:50,887 --> 00:14:53,350
I'm gonna keep this forever!

310
00:14:53,357 --> 00:14:57,260
All of Springfield fell head
over heels for Lisa.

311
00:14:57,507 --> 00:14:58,471
Here she comes.

312
00:14:58,478 --> 00:15:01,642
Quick, switch from internal
monologue to external dialogue!

313
00:15:01,648 --> 00:15:04,492
Shall we visit the commissary
to toast your success?

314
00:15:04,496 --> 00:15:05,442
Yeah, sure, Mel.

315
00:15:05,455 --> 00:15:07,943
Let me just wave one more
good-bye to my fans.

316
00:15:25,008 --> 00:15:30,090
While applause rained down on Lisa,
poor Krusty found himself parched.

317
00:15:30,106 --> 00:15:34,271
It's 3:32 a.m.,
which means it's time for

318
00:15:34,276 --> 00:15:38,022
Last Gasp with Krusty the Clown!

319
00:15:38,457 --> 00:15:40,370
Brought to you by Nappien,

320
00:15:40,375 --> 00:15:43,142
Nok-em-Out and
Nok-em-Out Jr. for kids.

321
00:15:43,147 --> 00:15:47,191
Tonight's guest is local bully,
Jimbo Jones?

322
00:15:50,338 --> 00:15:53,093
This is the lowest
I've ever sunk

323
00:15:53,095 --> 00:15:55,811
and I once made out
with a blow-up doll

324
00:16:03,137 --> 00:16:06,583
Sorry you broke up
with me now Cindy?

325
00:16:06,587 --> 00:16:09,530
One of these has got to be that
smooching Lincoln penny.

326
00:16:09,537 --> 00:16:11,581
Nope. Nope.
Dime. Button.

327
00:16:11,588 --> 00:16:13,082
- Pepperoni slice.
- Wait!

328
00:16:13,098 --> 00:16:16,752
This is a classic
1978 Pizza Hut!

329
00:16:18,027 --> 00:16:21,063
Mmm... terrible.

330
00:16:21,065 --> 00:16:23,252
Nope. Nope. Nope.

331
00:16:23,257 --> 00:16:26,452
Son, coin collecting's
a lot like life.

332
00:16:26,457 --> 00:16:29,561
It stopped being fun
a long time ago.

333
00:16:29,566 --> 00:16:32,770
But unlike life, I have
a solution for this.

334
00:16:32,825 --> 00:16:34,171
Gavelby's
Auction house.

335
00:16:34,175 --> 00:16:36,071
Going once, going twice...

336
00:16:36,075 --> 00:16:37,872
sold to Mr. Burns!

337
00:16:37,878 --> 00:16:39,412
I've won every coin.

338
00:16:39,417 --> 00:16:41,871
But I feel strangely empty.

339
00:16:41,876 --> 00:16:43,953
Ooh, there's another coin.
That should do it.

340
00:16:43,958 --> 00:16:48,770
Our last item up for bid is a mint
condition 1917 "Kissing Lincoln" penny.

341
00:16:48,788 --> 00:16:51,191
Okay, boy, this is it.
Five dollars!

342
00:16:51,195 --> 00:16:54,972
- $500.
- Five dollars cash!

343
00:16:54,977 --> 00:16:58,253
Sir, the promise of cash
is not an enticement.

344
00:16:58,258 --> 00:17:00,182
The current bid is $500.

345
00:17:00,188 --> 00:17:03,811
Do I hear a counter bid?
Going once, going twice...Dad?

346
00:17:03,818 --> 00:17:05,863
- $501!
- $10 million.

347
00:17:05,866 --> 00:17:08,380
- Objection, your honor.
- Sir, I am not a judge.

348
00:17:08,387 --> 00:17:12,532
But, um, overruled.
Sold to Mr. Burns for $10 million!

349
00:17:16,425 --> 00:17:20,691
I paid a pretty penny for this
pretty penny, but it was worth it.

350
00:17:22,077 --> 00:17:25,581
Mr. Burns, my son and
I have been collecting coins.

351
00:17:25,606 --> 00:17:28,330
It's really brought
us closer together.

352
00:17:28,347 --> 00:17:32,092
That penny you bought tonight
would mean the world to him.

353
00:17:32,098 --> 00:17:36,263
Yes, but the problem is,
if you had it, I wouldn't.

354
00:17:36,267 --> 00:17:37,793
You see difficulty.

355
00:17:37,797 --> 00:17:39,721
Mmm. Yeah.

356
00:17:39,728 --> 00:17:43,122
I'll tell you what, at least help
me buy the boy a gumball.

357
00:17:43,127 --> 00:17:45,821
- Do you have change for a nickel?
- Oh, of course.

358
00:17:46,746 --> 00:17:48,471
Smithers, step on it!

359
00:17:49,276 --> 00:17:51,540
I only gave him four cents
for that nickel.

360
00:17:51,545 --> 00:17:54,421
Monty Burns wins a...

361
00:17:54,616 --> 00:17:57,340
And... done.

362
00:17:57,358 --> 00:18:00,811
Now, let's put it on a shelf
and never look at it again.

363
00:18:00,817 --> 00:18:03,122
You got it, boy.

364
00:18:04,445 --> 00:18:07,273
And so, bonded by love
and larceny,

365
00:18:07,278 --> 00:18:09,760
father and son got dressed,

366
00:18:09,827 --> 00:18:11,623
had a minor disagreement...

367
00:18:11,627 --> 00:18:12,591
You little...

368
00:18:13,927 --> 00:18:15,352
...patched things up...

369
00:18:17,268 --> 00:18:18,681
Sorry, Dad.

370
00:18:18,688 --> 00:18:20,192
...and went downtown,

371
00:18:20,195 --> 00:18:22,120
where they watched proudly,

372
00:18:22,125 --> 00:18:25,000
as Lisa accepted her award.

373
00:18:31,075 --> 00:18:34,233
Lisa, before you walk away
from this venerable hall and

374
00:18:34,236 --> 00:18:38,041
into the arms of your adoring fans,
may I have a moment?

375
00:18:38,046 --> 00:18:41,102
Well, I do owe you everything.
Make it quick.

376
00:18:41,107 --> 00:18:45,463
Behold your fellow winners
of the Entertainer of the Year Award.

377
00:18:45,467 --> 00:18:47,641
Hmm.
I don't recognize any of them.

378
00:18:47,645 --> 00:18:49,453
And why should you?

379
00:18:49,458 --> 00:18:52,063
He appears nightly
on Broadway,

380
00:18:52,068 --> 00:18:54,701
selling combs and mints
in the men's room.

381
00:18:54,706 --> 00:18:57,543
She was fired after
a bad rehearsal

382
00:18:57,548 --> 00:18:59,910
from Homeboys In Outer Space.

383
00:18:59,918 --> 00:19:02,203
And perhaps
the saddest one of all,

384
00:19:02,207 --> 00:19:05,692
he graced stages from
London to Los Angeles.

385
00:19:05,698 --> 00:19:08,210
When he played
Biff in Death Of A Salesman,

386
00:19:08,218 --> 00:19:11,933
every woman in the audience
wished they were Hap.

387
00:19:11,948 --> 00:19:16,480
But that was before he...
"took the bone."

388
00:19:17,338 --> 00:19:20,551
Melvin Van Horne.

389
00:19:20,958 --> 00:19:22,973
Sideshow Mel?!

390
00:19:22,975 --> 00:19:24,093
It's you!

391
00:19:24,185 --> 00:19:28,021
How could this happen to you,
to all these wonderful performers?

392
00:19:28,026 --> 00:19:30,501
Applause is an addiction,

393
00:19:30,506 --> 00:19:33,760
like heroin or checking your e-mail.

394
00:19:33,776 --> 00:19:37,352
Once you have a taste,
you'll do anything to get more.

395
00:19:37,356 --> 00:19:39,601
Don't end up like these people.

396
00:19:39,608 --> 00:19:41,702
Don't end up like...

397
00:19:42,296 --> 00:19:43,410
me.

398
00:19:45,535 --> 00:19:47,873
I need to get out
while I still can.

399
00:19:47,875 --> 00:19:49,253
Thank you, Mel.

400
00:19:49,945 --> 00:19:51,370
Everyone, wait!

401
00:19:51,378 --> 00:19:53,790
Um, there's someone
I forgot to thank,

402
00:19:53,795 --> 00:19:55,131
and he's here tonight.

403
00:19:55,146 --> 00:19:57,533
Krusty, will you come up
on stage, please?

404
00:19:57,537 --> 00:19:58,751
What do you want?

405
00:19:58,755 --> 00:20:01,303
You've already taken
everything I care about.

406
00:20:01,306 --> 00:20:02,140
Really?

407
00:20:02,147 --> 00:20:04,040
So what else is in the news?

408
00:20:04,047 --> 00:20:06,701
This just in:
I don't give a crap.

409
00:20:06,706 --> 00:20:08,682
I'm trying to set you up
for laughs.

410
00:20:08,688 --> 00:20:10,873
Trying to set me up
with a giraffe?

411
00:20:12,306 --> 00:20:13,480
Oh, right.

412
00:20:13,488 --> 00:20:16,433
You guys know about giraffes...
long legs, big neck.

413
00:20:16,436 --> 00:20:17,781
Here comes the zinger.

414
00:20:17,788 --> 00:20:18,953
Speaking of necks,

415
00:20:18,957 --> 00:20:21,813
my girlfriend is
a real pain in mine.

416
00:20:21,816 --> 00:20:23,940
She crashed her car in
to mine and said,

417
00:20:23,946 --> 00:20:26,442
"Look, honey, we have a hybrid."

418
00:20:28,227 --> 00:20:29,491
Timely.

419
00:20:31,085 --> 00:20:33,352
By giving everything away,

420
00:20:33,357 --> 00:20:36,483
she was able to keep the only
thing that mattered:

421
00:20:36,485 --> 00:20:38,152
her dignity.

422
00:20:39,348 --> 00:20:42,060
God, how I envy her.

423
00:20:43,288 --> 00:20:45,930
Ooh, I think I'm in love!

424
00:20:45,938 --> 00:20:47,431
Krusty, please.

425
00:20:47,436 --> 00:20:49,902
My wife is giving birth
as we speak!

426
00:20:49,905 --> 00:20:52,123
Just four more takes.
Come on.

427
00:20:53,535 --> 00:20:54,331
No!

428
00:20:54,666 --> 00:20:56,480
Oh, Krusty, have a heart.

429
00:20:58,325 --> 00:21:01,322
Transcript: Raceman

430
00:21:01,405 --> 00:21:04,400
Sync: Job22

431
